      {
        "id": "c3e05587e49e9f771776403023594a8d1863dabc",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 3957,
          "name": "Samuli Silvius",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "s.silvius@partner.samsung.com",
          "username": "silvius"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2019-03-25 12:36:13.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nOk I have changed this part quite a bit in here: https://gerrit.onap.org/r/#/c/82628/\nJust have to check if it can be merged with that. Would prefer actually this chnage on top of my commit.",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "79e1bf956dea3adfb31006137fb0c9d6f7349007",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 5019,
          "name": "Michal Zegan",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "m.zegan@samsung.com",
          "username": "m.zegan"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2019-03-25 13:06:27.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nWell, I take a completely different approach here, instead of having an override role that may have any logic it desires, i just assume that all overrides can be statically passed by -e or application_configuration.yml or similar, and the only exception is the root certificate that needs to be merged with this.\nNot quite sure what is the use case for a separate override role then.",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "205aeae9b7b69c83175d151cb5c2ab08f7998f9b",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 3957,
          "name": "Samuli Silvius",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "s.silvius@partner.samsung.com",
          "username": "silvius"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2019-03-25 13:22:30.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> Well, I take a completely different approach here, instead of\n > having an override role that may have any logic it desires, i just\n > assume that all overrides can be statically passed by -e or\n > application_configuration.yml or similar, and the only exception is\n > the root certificate that needs to be merged with this.\n > Not quite sure what is the use case for a separate override role\n > then.\n\nYes but I think those approaches can be merged. Somehow we should merge anyway.\n\nFirst use case I wanted to add is the ability to skip override and not to have it mandatory.\n\nSecond use case I added is to move it to own role meaning user can write own role and code to generate the override file. That means override don't need to be static.\n\nThird use case I added is the possibility to define path and name for the override file.",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "c30f9a5bd41f0cb12de5d1c97d9c7d3f8e10254c",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 5019,
          "name": "Michal Zegan",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "m.zegan@samsung.com",
          "username": "m.zegan"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2019-03-25 13:35:19.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> > Well, I take a completely different approach here, instead of\n > > having an override role that may have any logic it desires, i\n > just\n > > assume that all overrides can be statically passed by -e or\n > > application_configuration.yml or similar, and the only exception\n > is\n > > the root certificate that needs to be merged with this.\n > > Not quite sure what is the use case for a separate override role\n > > then.\n > \n > Yes but I think those approaches can be merged. Somehow we should\n > merge anyway.\n > \n > First use case I wanted to add is the ability to skip override and\n > not to have it mandatory.\nThis would not require a role... Do you have any example where this override skip may be useful? Still, ok.\n > \n > Second use case I added is to move it to own role meaning user can\n > write own role and code to generate the override file. That means\n > override don't need to be static.\nThat was the question above, what is the use case for this? You mostly do not generate override stuff, except the certificate. I would guess that just having a list that you pass to installer is enough.\n > \n > Third use case I added is the possibility to define path and name\n > for the override file.\nAlso not quite sure what for... considering it is not the user passed file, it's contents are user passed, so it could be put in a static location, even in /tmp",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "5ea86080a4d6b4b359b30595cfb4bbca5fb00b32",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 3957,
          "name": "Samuli Silvius",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "s.silvius@partner.samsung.com",
          "username": "silvius"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2019-03-25 14:17:27.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> > > Well, I take a completely different approach here, instead of\n > > > having an override role that may have any logic it desires, i\n > > just\n > > > assume that all overrides can be statically passed by -e or\n > > > application_configuration.yml or similar, and the only\n > exception\n > > is\n > > > the root certificate that needs to be merged with this.\n > > > Not quite sure what is the use case for a separate override\n > role\n > > > then.\n > >\n > > Yes but I think those approaches can be merged. Somehow we should\n > > merge anyway.\n > >\n > > First use case I wanted to add is the ability to skip override\n > and\n > > not to have it mandatory.\n > This would not require a role... Do you have any example where this\n > override skip may be useful? Still, ok.\n > >\n > > Second use case I added is to move it to own role meaning user\n > can\n > > write own role and code to generate the override file. That means\n > > override don't need to be static.\n > That was the question above, what is the use case for this? You\n > mostly do not generate override stuff, except the certificate. I\n > would guess that just having a list that you pass to installer is\n > enough.\n > >\n > > Third use case I added is the possibility to define path and name\n > > for the override file.\n > Also not quite sure what for... considering it is not the user\n > passed file, it's contents are user passed, so it could be put in a\n > static location, even in /tmp\n\n\n\n > This would not require a role... Do you have any example where this\n > override skip may be useful? Still, ok.\n\nYes it does not need a role. Is the role a bad thing:)\nUse case: Install some other app than onap. OR onap as online (no certs).\n\n\n \n > You mostly do not generate override stuff, except the certificate. I\n > would guess that just having a list that you pass to installer is\n > enough.\n\n:) Well mostly we don't know, this just gives freedom to generate or give it statically.\nGiving a \"list\" to installer is not ruled out by this, right.\n\n\n> Also not quite sure what for... considering it is not the user\n > passed file,\n\nIf user passes the role code he may also prefer some own override file name/places.\nEven /tmp.",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
